  "_dft": {
    "_doc": "JTAG + boundary-scan demo (Layer 7).\n\n  Anatomy:\n    • CLOCK tck — drives the TAP and every BSC in lock-step.\n    • Three INPUTs tms / tdi / trst feed the TAP; pulse TMS to walk the 16-state FSM, drive TDI when shifting, raise TRST to force Test-Logic-Reset.\n    • JTAG_TAP — IEEE 1149.1 controller. STATE / IR / TDO are exported to OUTPUTs for visibility.\n    • Four BOUNDARY_SCAN_CELLs (bsc0..bsc3) form a scan ring around four 'core' inputs (core0..core3). MODE / SHIFT are gated by the TAP's STATE and IR via small combinational helpers (here driven directly by external inputs to keep the demo readable).\n    • Outputs po0..po3 show the cells' pad outputs (passing through in normal mode, latched-test value in test mode); so0..so3 expose the per-cell shift bits so the chain is visible.\n\n  Suggested play:\n    1. Open the DFT panel and scroll to JTAG TAPS — see TAP state name change as you toggle TMS and STEP.\n    2. From TLR (5×TMS=1), navigate TMS=0 → Run-Test/Idle, then TMS=1,1,0,0 → Shift-DR. Now each STEP shifts TDI through the chain (watch DR climb in the panel).\n    3. Switch SHIFT=1, MODE=0 to load the BSC chain from SI; switch MODE=1 to drive the latched bits onto po0..po3 in test mode."
  },
